---
export const prerender = true;
import ChapterLayout from '../layouts/ChapterLayout.astro';
import { chapters } from '../data/chapters';
import FadeInBlock from '../components/scroll/FadeInBlock';
import AccentBar from '../components/ui/AccentBar';
import Divider from '../components/ui/Divider';
import DebugDetective from '../components/widgets/ch9/DebugDetective';
import EvalFramework from '../components/breaks/EvalFramework';
import BreakReveal from '../components/breaks/BreakReveal';
import SharePrompt from '../components/ui/SharePrompt';
import ForYouCard from '../components/ui/ForYouCard';

const chapter = chapters[8];
const conceptsSummary = chapter.concepts.map(c => c.name).join(', ');
---

<ChapterLayout chapter={chapter}>

  <!-- ═══ HERO ═══ -->
  <section class="min-h-[80vh] flex flex-col items-center justify-end px-6 pb-20 relative overflow-hidden">
    <div class="chapter-number" style={`color: ${chapter.accent};`}>9</div>

    <div class="max-w-[680px] mx-auto text-center relative z-10">
      <FadeInBlock client:visible>
        <p class="text-[13px] italic text-subtle/60 mb-5" style="font-family: var(--font-body);">
          Chapter Nine
        </p>
      </FadeInBlock>

      <FadeInBlock client:visible delay={0.15}>
        <h1
          class="mb-8 leading-[1.08]"
          style={`font-family: var(--font-heading); color: ${chapter.accent}; font-size: clamp(2.8rem, 7vw, 4.5rem); font-weight: 800; letter-spacing: -0.03em;`}
        >
          The Build<br />Loop
        </h1>
      </FadeInBlock>

      <FadeInBlock client:visible delay={0.3}>
        <p class="text-lg md:text-xl italic text-deep/40 leading-relaxed max-w-sm mx-auto" style="font-family: var(--font-body);">
          Expect imperfection. Enjoy refinement.<br />The third version is where the magic happens.
        </p>
      </FadeInBlock>
    </div>

    <div class="absolute bottom-6 left-1/2 -translate-x-1/2 opacity-20 animate-pulse">
      <div class="w-px h-10 bg-deep/40"></div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ═══ OPENING HOOK ═══ -->
  <section class="max-w-[680px] mx-auto px-6 md:px-10 pt-24 pb-16">
    <FadeInBlock client:visible>
      <p class="text-lg leading-[1.85] drop-cap" style="margin: 0;">
        The most common mistake when building with AI isn't a bad prompt. It's a bad expectation. You type one long description, hit enter, and expect a finished product. It doesn't work. It never works. The people who build amazing things with AI know a secret: <strong>the first version is always wrong.</strong> The third version is good. The fifth is great. And the process of getting from one to five? That's the actual skill.
      </p>
    </FadeInBlock>

    <FadeInBlock client:visible delay={0.1}>
      <p class="text-lg leading-[1.85] mt-8">
        Every artist iterates. Every architect revises. Every filmmaker shoots multiple takes. Building with AI is no different. The people who enjoy the loop &mdash; not resent it &mdash; are the ones who build the best things.
      </p>
    </FadeInBlock>
  </section>

  <Divider accent={chapter.accent} client:load />

  <!-- ═══ THE LOOP ═══ -->
  <section class="max-w-[680px] mx-auto px-6 md:px-10 py-16">
    <FadeInBlock client:visible>
      <AccentBar color={chapter.accent} className="w-16 mb-10" client:visible />
      <h2 class="mb-8" style="font-family: var(--font-heading);">
        Specify, Generate, Verify
      </h2>
    </FadeInBlock>

    <FadeInBlock client:visible delay={0.1}>
      <p class="text-lg leading-[1.85] mb-14" style="margin-top: 0;">
        Every productive session with a coding agent follows the same rhythm. <strong>Specify</strong> what you want &mdash; be concrete, give examples, describe what "done" looks like. Let the agent <strong>generate</strong> it. Then <strong>verify</strong>: does it work? Does it look right? Does it do what you asked? If not, you specify again, more precisely. That's the loop. It's not a sign of failure. It's the process.
      </p>
    </FadeInBlock>

    <FadeInBlock client:visible delay={0.2}>
      <p class="text-lg leading-[1.85] mb-14">
        The power move is writing your <strong>acceptance criteria</strong> before you start building. "The button should turn green when clicked." "The list should persist when I refresh the page." "The signup form should reject emails without an @ symbol." These plain-English descriptions of "done" become your evaluation framework. When something's wrong, you paste your criteria back to the agent and say "this doesn't match." The agent can test against <em>your</em> standards.
      </p>
    </FadeInBlock>
  </section>

  <Divider accent={chapter.accent} client:load />

  <!-- ═══ WHEN STUCK ═══ -->
  <section class="max-w-[680px] mx-auto px-6 md:px-10 py-16">
    <FadeInBlock client:visible>
      <AccentBar color={chapter.accent} className="w-16 mb-10" client:visible />
      <h2 class="mb-8" style="font-family: var(--font-heading);">
        What to Do When You're Stuck
      </h2>
    </FadeInBlock>

    <FadeInBlock client:visible delay={0.1}>
      <p class="text-lg leading-[1.85] mb-10" style="margin-top: 0;">
        The agent generated something broken. Now what? Five strategies, in order of what to try first:
      </p>
    </FadeInBlock>

    <FadeInBlock client:visible delay={0.15}>
      <div style="display: grid; gap: 0.75rem; margin-bottom: 2rem;">
        <div style="padding: 1rem 1.25rem; background: rgba(22,199,154,0.04); border-radius: 8px; border: 1px solid rgba(22,199,154,0.1);">
          <p style="font-family: var(--font-heading); font-weight: 700; font-size: 0.9rem; margin: 0 0 0.25rem; color: #16C79A;">1. Describe the symptom, not your diagnosis</p>
          <p style="margin: 0; font-size: 0.95rem; line-height: 1.6;">"The button doesn't respond when I click it" beats "I think the onClick handler is broken."</p>
        </div>
        <div style="padding: 1rem 1.25rem; background: rgba(123,97,255,0.04); border-radius: 8px; border: 1px solid rgba(123,97,255,0.1);">
          <p style="font-family: var(--font-heading); font-weight: 700; font-size: 0.9rem; margin: 0 0 0.25rem; color: #7B61FF;">2. Share the error message verbatim</p>
          <p style="margin: 0; font-size: 0.95rem; line-height: 1.6;">Copy-paste the exact error. It's the single most useful thing you can give the agent.</p>
        </div>
        <div style="padding: 1rem 1.25rem; background: rgba(14,165,233,0.04); border-radius: 8px; border: 1px solid rgba(14,165,233,0.1);">
          <p style="font-family: var(--font-heading); font-weight: 700; font-size: 0.9rem; margin: 0 0 0.25rem; color: #0EA5E9;">3. Ask the agent to explain what it did</p>
          <p style="margin: 0; font-size: 0.95rem; line-height: 1.6;">"Walk me through what you just changed and why." Understanding often reveals the issue.</p>
        </div>
        <div style="padding: 1rem 1.25rem; background: rgba(245,166,35,0.04); border-radius: 8px; border: 1px solid rgba(245,166,35,0.1);">
          <p style="font-family: var(--font-heading); font-weight: 700; font-size: 0.9rem; margin: 0 0 0.25rem; color: #F5A623;">4. Ask for a different approach</p>
          <p style="margin: 0; font-size: 0.95rem; line-height: 1.6;">"That approach isn't working. Can you try solving this a completely different way?"</p>
        </div>
        <div style="padding: 1rem 1.25rem; background: rgba(233,69,96,0.04); border-radius: 8px; border: 1px solid rgba(233,69,96,0.1);">
          <p style="font-family: var(--font-heading); font-weight: 700; font-size: 0.9rem; margin: 0 0 0.25rem; color: #E94560;">5. Start fresh with lessons learned</p>
          <p style="margin: 0; font-size: 0.95rem; line-height: 1.6;">Sometimes a new conversation is faster than debugging a tangled one. Bring the key decisions with you.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </FadeInBlock>

    <FadeInBlock client:visible delay={0.3}>
      <div class="insight-box">
        <p style={`font-family: var(--font-heading); font-size: 0.85rem; font-weight: 700; color: ${chapter.accent}; margin: 0 0 0.5rem;`}>Tests as guardrails</p>
        <p style="font-size: 1rem; line-height: 1.75; margin: 0;">
          You can ask the agent to write automated tests &mdash; in plain English. "Write a test that verifies the signup form rejects emails without an @ symbol." The agent writes the test <em>and</em> the code that passes it. This is test-driven development, directed by someone who's never written a test. Once a bug is caught by a test, it can never come back.
        </p>
      </div>
    </FadeInBlock>
  </section>

  <!-- ═══ WIDGET BRIDGE ═══ -->
  <section class="max-w-[680px] mx-auto px-6 md:px-10 pt-4 pb-8">
    <FadeInBlock client:visible>
      <p class="text-lg leading-[1.85] text-center mx-auto italic text-deep/50" style="font-family: var(--font-body); text-wrap: balance;">
        Practice the skill. How would you describe these bugs to a coding agent?
      </p>
    </FadeInBlock>
  </section>

  <!-- ═══ THE WIDGET ═══ -->
  <section class="max-w-[900px] mx-auto px-6 md:px-10 py-8">
    <DebugDetective client:visible />
  </section>

  <Divider accent={chapter.accent} client:load />

  <div class="py-8">
    <ForYouCard
      chapterSlug={chapter.slug}
      chapterTitle={chapter.title}
      chapterConcepts={conceptsSummary}
      accentColor={chapter.accent}
      client:load
    />
  </div>
  <SharePrompt text="This chapter on building with AI coding agents is gold. The 5 debugging strategies alone are worth it — describe symptoms, share errors, ask for explanations." client:visible />

  <!-- ═══ SEND-OFF ═══ -->
  <section class="max-w-[680px] mx-auto px-6 md:px-10 py-24">
    <FadeInBlock client:visible>
      <div class="pull-quote" style={`border-color: ${chapter.accent}; max-width: 50ch; margin: 0 auto 2rem;`}>
        The first version is always wrong. The third is good. The fifth is great. Enjoy the loop.
      </div>
    </FadeInBlock>

    <FadeInBlock client:visible delay={0.1}>
      <p class="text-lg leading-[1.85] text-center mx-auto" style="max-width: 55ch;">
        You can iterate. You can debug. But how do you know if what you're building is actually <em>good</em>? Not just functional &mdash; good. That takes something AI can't give you: taste. That's next.
      </p>
    </FadeInBlock>
  </section>

  <!-- ═══ BREAK ═══ -->
  <section id="break" class="py-16 px-6" style="background: linear-gradient(180deg, var(--color-cream) 0%, rgba(233,69,96,0.06) 15%, rgba(233,69,96,0.06) 85%, var(--color-cream) 100%);">
    <div class="max-w-[900px] mx-auto">
      <BreakReveal accentColor="#E94560" toolName="Eval Framework" client:visible>
        <EvalFramework client:visible />
      </BreakReveal>
    </div>
  </section>

</ChapterLayout>
